## 6. Regional Case Studies

| Region            | Method of Spread                 | Key Features                                                                                                         | Outcome                                                                                  |
|-------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Middle East & North Africa** | Military conquest, administration | Rapid Arab conquests; establishment of caliphates; tolerance of "People of the Book"; Arabic language spread          | Islam became dominant religion; Arabic culture flourished                               |
| **West Africa**    | Trade, elite conversion          | Trans-Saharan trade; conversion of rulers like Mansa Musa; limited initial mass conversion                            | Islam became major religion; centers like Timbuktu emerged                              |
| **East Africa**    | Trade, Sufi missionaries         | Coastal trading towns; Swahili culture; Sufi influence                                                             | Gradual Islamization of coastal and some inland areas                                  |
| **Central Asia**   | Conquest, Sufi missionary work   | Turkic migrations; Mongol conversions; Sufi orders like Naqshbandi                                                  | Islam became dominant religion among Turkic and Mongol peoples                         |
| **Indian Subcontinent** | Trade, conquest, missionary work | Arab traders; Turkish and Mughal conquests; Sufi missionary activity; syncretism with Hinduism                       | Islam became significant minority; cultural blending; emergence of Muslim empires      |
| **Southeast Asia** | Trade, Sufi missionaries         | Muslim merchant networks; conversion of local rulers; syncretism with Hindu-Buddhist traditions                      | Islam became dominant religion in many areas; formation of sultanates                   |
| **Europe (Spain & Balkans)** | Military conquest, administration | Umayyad conquest of Iberia; Ottoman conquest of Balkans; coexistence with Christian and Jewish populations           | Muslim rule lasted centuries; cultural exchanges; eventual Christian reconquest         |

